`torch.nn.Module` is the base class for every PyTorch model — you subclass it, define your layers in `__init__`, and define the forward pass in `forward()`; PyTorch automatically tracks every parameter declared on `self` so the optimizer can find and update them later. `nn.Linear(in_features, out_features)` is the `w·x + b` layer from the linear-regression topic, and `nn.Sequential` chains layers (and activations) in order when you don't need anything more custom than a straight pipeline:
```python
import torch.nn as nn

class MLP(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, in_dim, hidden_dim, out_dim):
        super().__init__()
        self.net = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(in_dim, hidden_dim),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(hidden_dim, out_dim),
        )

    def forward(self, x):
        return self.net(x)

model = MLP(in_dim=2, hidden_dim=16, out_dim=1)
```
This pattern — `__init__` declares layers, `forward` defines the data flow through them — is identical whether you're building this 2-layer toy MLP or, later, wrapping a pretrained transformer for fine-tuning; only the layers inside change.
